["Course Objective
This course consists of two parts, each with its own goals.
Learning goals part 1:
The student is able to write down a statistical model for cellular evolution;
The student can analyse the properties of such models;
The student is able to make inferences using these models and perform generalisations;
The student understands the stochastic description of a gene-gene interaction network and knows how to reconstruct such a network data.
Learning goals part 2:
The student is able to model biological processes that involve time-dependent dynamics (both in discrete and continuous time);
The student can perform an analysis of such a model, consisting of finding steady states and their stability properties using linear stability analysis, and can describe the effects on solutions of parameter perturbations;
The student is able to interpret the mathematical results back into the biomedical context;
The student is able to study the long-time behaviour of solutions using the concept of dominant eigenvalues.", "Course Content
This course consists of two parts.
The first parts has two sections. In both sections processes in the cell are modelled. An event in a cell does not occur in isolation, but occurs in relation to the rest of the cell. In the entire course these dependencies are modelled. Wherever possible examples from the VUmc medical hospotical are used to illustrate statistical techniques. In the first section of this part we focus on modelling DNA sequences. The resulting models are used to describe the evolution of cancer cells. Using hidden Markov chain models the exon-intron structure of a gene is studied. We also describe the evolution of DNA to reconstruct phylogenetic trees (trees of descent). In the second section, we try to unravel the topological structure of gene regulatory networks on the basis of gene expression data. Can we uncover which genes works together?
In the second part of the course, we will cover deterministic models of biological processes, using both discrete and continuous time models. We will treat how to set up equations, analyse the resulting model and how to interpret the results back into the biological context. We will cover various biological and biomedical applications, such as ecology, epidemiology and chemical reactions.", "Additional Information Teaching Methods
Lectures and written assignments", "Method of Assessment
For the first part, there is only a written exam. For the second part there are hand-in assignments (10%) and a written exam (90%). Both parts need to be passed with a grade of 5.5 or higher.
The resit procedure is as follows. If a student fails to pass one or both parts, he/she needs to take part in the resit. The resit is one exam, consisting of two separate parts. If you fail just one part, you only need to make the questions for that part. For the resit of part 2: the mark for your assignments only counts towards your resit mark if this has a positive outcome on your average mark. If not, the assignment marks do not count towards the resit mark.", "Additional Information Target Audience
Bachelor Mathematics year 3", "Recommended background knowledge
Linear Algebra, Dynamical Systems, Probability Theory"]

["Course Objective
The course has the following learning objectives:
Conducting independent architectural historical research;
Learning to critically analyze and interpret design concepts and discourses within architecture, urbanism and landscape architecture and to place these designs, concepts and discourses in a historical context;
Learning to work with historical and contemporary written sources and research archives;
Continuing to practice reading floor plans, elevations, sections and axonometries;
Presenting scientific research orally to peers;
Practicing giving (substantive) feedback on the presentation of fellow students;
The processing of research results into a scientific article or similar work at level 300.", "Course Content
The Architecture Research Seminar is focused on analyzing and interpreting spatial plans and designs. The subject of the seminar varies each year and will be announced in advance through Canvas. The lecture series starts with the study and joint discussion of the professional, spatial and historical context of the chosen architectural, urban design and/or landscape architectural ensemble, subject or period. Then several case studies are analyzed and interpreted together using the available visual, design and presentation material (sketches, drawings, models) and written primary and secondary sources. Each student then formulates an individual research theme that is further questioned, researched and contextualized and reports on it in the form of a scientific article or a comparable piece of work.", "Additional Information Teaching Methods
Lectures and seminars with active participation, field trip(s), oral presentation(s) and a final written paper. Depending on the topic of the seminar, some of the meetings will take place on location, in an archive or at a (research) institute.", "Method of Assessment
Oral presentation (30%); written paper (70%)
In order to complete the course with a passing grade, the written paper must receive at least a 6.0. For a grade lower lower than a 6.0 on the first submission, there is one retake.
Alignment of leaning objectives and test formats:
Learning objective 1, 2, 3, 4, 7: presentation and paper;
Learning objective 5, 6: presentation.
Final Attainment Levels (eindtermen) BA MKDA: 1,2,3,4,5,6,8,9,12", "Entry Requirements
See the Onderwijs- en Examenregeling (OER), c.q. Teaching and Exam Regulations (TER) for MKDA.", "Literature
A list of mandatory class literature will be published on Canvas and/or the Study Manual.", "Additional Information Target Audience
